question: What is the purpose of Mapping of Address and Port (MAP)?

options.A: Mapping of Address and Port (MAP) is a proposal that focuses on improving the performance and reliability of internet connections. It uses the extra bits available in the IPv6 address to contain the extra port range identifier bits of the A+P addressing pair that cannot be encoded directly into the IPv4 address. This method ensures faster and more stable data transmission between networks.
options.B: Mapping of Address and Port (MAP) is a proposal that addresses the scalability issues of existing network architectures. It combines A+P port address translation with the tunneling of legacy IPv4 protocol packets over an ISP's internal IPv6 network. This approach provides greater flexibility in managing address and port assignments, resulting in more efficient network utilization.
options.C: Mapping of Address and Port (MAP) is a proposal that combines A+P port address translation with the tunneling of legacy IPv4 protocol packets over an ISP's internal IPv6 network. MAP uses the extra bits available in the IPv6 address to contain the extra port range identifier bits of the A+P addressing pair that cannot be encoded directly into the IPv4 address, thus completely eliminating the need for "port routing" within the carrier network by leveraging the provider's own IPv6 rollout.
options.D: Mapping of Address and Port (MAP) is a proposal that simplifies the process of migrating from IPv4 to IPv6. It combines A+P port address translation with the tunneling of legacy IPv4 protocol packets over an ISP's internal IPv6 network. MAP utilizes the extra bits available in the IPv6 address to contain the extra port range identifier bits of the A+P addressing pair that cannot be encoded directly into the IPv4 address, resulting in a seamless transition between the two protocols.
options.E: Mapping of Address and Port (MAP) is a proposal that aims to enhance the security of internal networks by implementing address and port translation protocols. It uses the extra bits available in the IPv6 address to contain the extra port range identifier bits of the A+P addressing pair that cannot be encoded directly into the IPv4 address.
